Sep 25 2006 	OK but comments on specific rooms	I stayed there with 4 of my friends. We originally had booked two doubles and a single, but when we saw the rooms, we changed to a double and a triple. The single we were shown was in the basement down a small, twisty staircase . It was a tiny, dark room with an even tinier shower stall/WC and none of us wanted it. So two people ended up in room 3, and three of us ended up in room 9. Room 3 wasn't bad. It was the easiest room in the hotel to reach: it was up the first flight of stairs: a straight shot. The room had cross ventilation, and a decent sized shower stall/WC. Room 9 was up a floor or two more and you had to go around corners/landings. 9 did not have cross ventilation, and it was hot! The bathroom was very small, probably like what you would find in a recreational vehicle or a boat. I've included a photo of the bathroom in room 9. Both 3 and 9 looked out the back of the building, really not much of a view, but probably quieter than if we had been fronting Sussex Gardens. The staff was nice, and the breakfasts were fine. The rooms were acceptably clean. The staff did help us bring our bags up when we arrived. You still have to check in with the hotel 2 doors down (same management/ownership.) One possible problem in the future: apparently they have applied to have a bar/club in the evenings on the ground floor. I got the feeling it might be open to the public, not just the people staying there. Not sure how that will work out as far as noise, and security.	
